

# ğŸ¥ Insurance Premium Prediction (Regression Project)

## ğŸ“Œ Project Overview

This project builds a **machine learning regression system** to predict **insurance premiums** based on customer information such as age, BMI, smoking status, region, and number of dependents.

The main goal is not only to predict premiums accurately, but also to **analyze model performance across different customer segments** (age groups and BMI categories) to ensure fairness and reliability.

---

## ğŸ¯ Objectives

* Predict insurance premiums using regression models
* Engineer meaningful features such as **age bands** and **BMI bands**
* Compare a **baseline model** with a **boosting model**
* Perform **segment-wise error analysis**
* Report **Mean Absolute Error (MAE)** for different customer groups

---

## ğŸ“‚ Dataset Description

A synthetic insurance-style dataset is used with the following features:

### Input Features

| Feature      | Description                          |
| ------------ | ------------------------------------ |
| `age`        | Age of the customer                  |
| `BMI`        | Body Mass Index                      |
| `smoker`     | Whether the customer smokes (Yes/No) |
| `dependents` | Number of dependents                 |
| `region`     | Residential region                   |
| `age_band`   | Age category (engineered)            |
| `bmi_band`   | BMI category (engineered)            |

### Target Variable

| Feature             | Description                    |
| ------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| `insurance_premium` | Insurance cost to be predicted |

---

## ğŸ›  Feature Engineering

### 1ï¸âƒ£ Age Bands

Customers are grouped into age categories:

* 18â€“25
* 26â€“35
* 36â€“45
* 46â€“55
* 56â€“65

This helps the model learn age-related pricing patterns.

---

### 2ï¸âƒ£ BMI Bands

BMI values are categorized into:

* Underweight
* Normal
* Overweight
* Obese

This captures health-risk related cost differences.

---

## âš™ï¸ Data Preprocessing

* One-Hot Encoding applied to categorical features:

  * `smoker`
  * `region`
  * `age_band`
  * `bmi_band`
* Dataset split into **training** and **testing** sets
* Target variable separated before training

---

## ğŸ¤– Models Used

### ğŸ”¹ Baseline Model

**Linear Regression**

* Simple and interpretable
* Used as a benchmark

### ğŸ”¹ Advanced Model

**Gradient Boosting Regressor**

* Ensemble learning method
* Captures non-linear relationships
* Provides better accuracy

---

## ğŸ“ Evaluation Metric

### Mean Absolute Error (MAE)

MAE measures the **average absolute difference** between predicted and actual premiums.

[
MAE = \frac{1}{n} \sum |y_{true} - y_{pred}|
]

Lower MAE means better performance.

---

## ğŸ“Š Segment-Wise Error Analysis

To check model fairness and consistency, MAE is calculated for different customer segments.

---

### ğŸ”¹ MAE by Age Band

| Age Band | MAE   |
| -------- | ----- |
| 18â€“25    | 82.72 |
| 26â€“35    | 91.26 |
| 36â€“45    | 82.52 |
| 46â€“55    | 92.65 |
| 56â€“65    | 99.16 |

**Observation:**

* Model performs best for young and middle-aged customers
* Higher error for older customers (56â€“65)

---

### ğŸ”¹ MAE by BMI Band

| BMI Band    | MAE   |
| ----------- | ----- |
| Underweight | 89.52 |
| Normal      | 99.27 |
| Overweight  | 89.71 |
| Obese       | 79.12 |

**Observation:**

* Best performance for obese customers
* Normal BMI group shows higher prediction error

---

## âœ… Key Findings

* Boosting model outperforms baseline regression
* Feature engineering improves predictive power
* Model performance varies across customer segments
* Segment analysis helps detect weak areas for improvement

